        ],
        "final_recommendation": "revise",
        "outstanding_questions": [
          "iao: namespace authority (I4): is the project willing to coordinate with IAO for a real OntologyDesignPattern and isAbout binding (slow, citable, externally verifiable), or to re-mint under ecm: with an explicit acknowledgement that the realist-anchoring claim becomes project-internal rather than IAO-anchored? The choice changes the framing of NFR-014 and DoD items 1, 2, 11.",
          "UUIDv5 namespace constant (I5): does the project want a fixed published namespace UUID (e.g., a UUIDv5 derived from a fixed DNS namespace + 'graphwrite.spec.v0.4'), or seed-dependent (project-specific) namespaces? Either is RFC-conformant; the choice is policy.",
          "Layer model reconciliation (I6): is SPEC sec 4.1 to be rewritten against the three-layer model (and CLAUDE.md/ARCHITECTURE.md/test:purity treated as authoritative), or are CLAUDE.md/ARCHITECTURE.md/test:purity to be revised to a five-layer model? The choice affects which existing kernel-purity tests stay valid.",
          "SPEC vs ROADMAP product alignment (I11): is ROADMAP.md to be rewritten as the SPEC sec 29 six-phase plan (and the generic-template framing dropped), or is the SPEC scope to be narrowed back to a generic JSON-LD service? CLAUDE.md sec 5 routes session planning through ROADMAP.md, so this choice gates every future agent session.",
          "TBox inline policy (I17): is the canonical project.jsonld permitted to carry the TBox inline (and sec 5.3 must specify canonical ordering for inlined TBox terms), or is TBox MUST-NOT-inline in canonical form (and sec 5.14:597 'at user's request' clause must be removed)?",
          "ecm:contentHash dual semantics (I19): split into two predicates (ecm:ontologyContentHash informational, ecm:serializationContentHash normative), or retain one predicate with subject-type-conditioned rules declared in sec 5.2? Linked-data consumers will see different shapes for the same data."
        ],
        "summary": "Synthesis of spec-reviewer's 19 findings and adversarial-critic's verdicts yields 27 dedup'd issues: 5 blocking (I1 version coherence, I2 severity taxonomy contradiction, I3 v0.3->v0.4 migration FR-C gap, I4 iao: namespace structural break covering F4+M1, I5 UUIDv5 underspecification), 12 major (I6 layer-model conflict, I7-I9 sec 6.1 allowlist gaps, I10 disjoint kernel error vocab + missing rulesApplied, I11 SPEC/ROADMAP product divergence, I12 cco: pinning, I13 DECISIONS.md template placeholder, I20 canvas-layout ordering, I21 scalar-vs-array @type, I22 sec 5.14/7.5 internal contradiction, I23 adapter-state discard rule), 7 minor (I14 stale v0.3 qualifiers, I15 missing @type on string fields, I16 missing RFC 2119, I17 inline TBox, I24-I26 sec 5.12/5.5/17.2 gaps), 3 advisory (I18 unplaced fnsr_daemon orchestrator, I19 ecm:contentHash dual role, I27 starter iao:isAbout pinning). The critic's overall verdict 'reviewer_under_rigorous' is upheld: every reviewer finding was confirmed (with three sharpened by extension \u00e2\u20ac\u201d I3, I12, I14, I17), and the critic surfaced four structurally important defects the reviewer missed entirely (I20 canvas ordering, I21 @type form, I22 TBox/sec 7.5 internal contradiction, I23 adapter-state discard) plus one blocking defect (M1, merged into I4) that deepens the iao: namespace problem from a single mis-minted class IRI into a complete @context-binding failure that makes iao:isAbout itself unreachable. Five un-refuted blocking issues and twelve un-refuted major issues force the final_recommendation to 'revise'. The acceptance gate's five required resolutions (from reviewer's gate) must be extended by at least: (a) the iao: namespace binding fix (I4), (b) the canvas-layout nested-array ordering rule (I20), (c) the @type scalar-vs-array canonical form (I21), (d) the sec 5.14 / sec 7.5 TBox-domain/range reconciliation (I22), and (e) the sec 5.11 adapter-state discard semantics (I23) before v0.4 can be called engineering-ready."
      },
      "depends_on": [
        "urn:fnsr:task:001-review",
        "urn:fnsr:task:002-critique"
      ],
