    {
      "@id": "urn:fnsr:task:003-roadmap-review",
      "agent": "spec-reviewer",
      "status": "done",
      "inputs": {
        "artifact": "Project Roadmap",
        "artifact_path": "project/ROADMAP.md",
        "focus": "completeness vs SPEC, phase ordering, scope-boundary clarity, missing concerns, ambiguous deferred decisions"
      },
      "outputs": {
        "findings": [
          {
            "id": "F1",
            "severity": "major",
            "claim": "Phase 4 scope duplicates work that ROADMAP Phase 1 already commits to, creating a contradictory ownership of export-format conformance goldens.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP Phase 1 scope states: 'Test harness (\u00c2\u00a721.1): unit, property-based invariants \u00e2\u20ac\u00a6, round-trip, golden-file, CLI integration, conformance, and deterministic-mode CI job (\u00c2\u00a721.4).' This implies golden files for emitter outputs (FR-C003\u00e2\u20ac\u201cC008) land in Phase 1. ROADMAP Phase 4 scope then states: 'Conformance goldens added for every export format, byte-compared in CI (\u00c2\u00a721.1, NFR-013).' Either Phase 1's 'golden-file \u00e2\u20ac\u00a6 conformance' coverage excludes the emitter formats (in which case Phase 1 cannot satisfy \u00c2\u00a721.1, which mandates 'Each starter example has committed golden files for project.jsonld, graph.ttl, graph.nt, graph.jsonld, default.mmd, and model-summary.md'), or Phase 4 is redundant. The roadmap does not say which."
          },
          {
            "id": "F2",
            "severity": "major",
            "claim": "OED-303 (Validation report retention) is deferred to Phase 3 but resolves a VMP profile shape question that must be settled before Phase 1 freezes canonical serialization.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP Phase 3 'Decisions Deferred' lists 'OED-303 (Validation report retention). Latest only, or one per save? Affects how the import-time validation report integrates with the project's ecm:validationReports array.' But the ecm:validationReports array is defined in SPEC \u00c2\u00a75.13 as part of project metadata (\u00c2\u00a75.4), which is canonical VMP shape. SPEC \u00c2\u00a75.3 requires byte-identical canonical serialization (NFR-013) on Phase 1 outputs; if Phase 3 later changes retention semantics, Phase 1 golden files (including the validation report fixture in \u00c2\u00a719's /reports/validation-report.jsonld) will break. The decision belongs in Phase 1, not Phase 3."
          },
          {
            "id": "F3",
            "severity": "major",
            "claim": "Phase 6 commits to verifying DoD \u00c2\u00a714 (byte-identical outputs across two independent implementations) without the roadmap accounting anywhere for the existence of a second implementation.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP Phase 6 scope: 'Final v0.4 Definition of Done verification per \u00c2\u00a731: realist-anchored conformance fixtures pass; TBox prepending and manifest realist-typing verified; byte-identical golden suite green across two independent implementations.' SPEC \u00c2\u00a731 DoD item 14: 'Two compliant implementations produce byte-identical canonical and derived artifacts for the conformance fixtures.' No phase in the ROADMAP \u00e2\u20ac\u201d including the Cross-Cutting Commitments \u00e2\u20ac\u201d schedules, scopes, staffs, or even names a second implementation. The DoD step in Phase 6 is therefore aspirational rather than executable. SPEC \u00c2\u00a729 has the same gap, but the ROADMAP is the document that is supposed to translate SPEC \u00c2\u00a729 into delivery sequencing."
          },
          {
            "id": "F4",
            "severity": "major",
            "claim": "Cross-Cutting Commitments omit NFRs that the SPEC treats as system-wide invariants, narrowing the binding constraints set in a way that is not justified.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP \u00c2\u00a7'Cross-Cutting Commitments' enumerates: realist anchoring (NFR-014), edge canonical (NFR-001/002), determinism (NFR-003/013), layering (NFR-005), offline (NFR-006), JSON-LD canonical (NFR-004). It does NOT list NFR-007 (no lock-in / open formats), NFR-008 (UI explains semantic modeling per \u00c2\u00a725), NFR-009 (UI exposes IRIs, RDF, terms, triples, serializations), NFR-010 (canvas prioritizes understandable modeling), NFR-011 (performance bounds per \u00c2\u00a714.2/\u00c2\u00a714.3), or NFR-012 (lossless canonical round-trip per \u00c2\u00a75.3, \u00c2\u00a76.4). NFR-012 in particular is a determinism-adjacent invariant that constrains every phase touching state. NFR-011 binds Phase 3 (large-import) and Phase 5 (persistence). Their absence from the cross-cutting set means phases can silently drop them and still appear 'done.'"
          },
          {
            "id": "F5",
            "severity": "major",
            "claim": "Phase 5 places OED-302 (IndexedDB schema versioning) in 'Decisions Deferred' alongside the IndexedDB implementation itself, with no ordering constraint that requires the decision before the implementation.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP Phase 5 scope: 'IndexedDB adapter with lossless canonical-document storage and recent-projects project picker (FR-S003\u00e2\u20ac\u201cFR-S004).' ROADMAP Phase 5 'Decisions Deferred': 'OED-302 (IndexedDB schema versioning). How IndexedDB schema migrations are coordinated with ecm:specVersion bumps.' Schema versioning determines the keyspace, object-store layout, and migration paths of the very adapter the phase ships. Building first and resolving the migration story afterward inverts the dependency. The roadmap does not state that OED-302 must be closed before implementation begins."
          },
          {
            "id": "F6",
            "severity": "major",
            "claim": "Phase 6 admits new validator findings beyond the \u00c2\u00a717 catalog without disclosing how they are represented, suppressed, or persisted, opening a scope-drift surface around the validator contract.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP Phase 6 scope: 'Modeling hints and early semantic-linter warnings beyond the \u00c2\u00a717 validator \u00e2\u20ac\u201d heuristics surfaced as info findings, not new hard errors.' SPEC \u00c2\u00a717.4 lists the closed set of info findings (LEGACY_DOCUMENT_MIGRATED, LEGACY_REALIST_ANCHOR_PLACEHOLDER, NORMALIZED_ON_SAVE). Adding new info findings touches ValidationReport shape (\u00c2\u00a75.13), suppression behavior (\u00c2\u00a717.5), report retention (OED-303), and the \u00c2\u00a717.5 'per-finding, per-target' acknowledgement scheme. The ROADMAP does not say where these heuristic codes are registered, whether they participate in the existing acknowledgement mechanism, or whether they appear in /reports/validation-report.jsonld. The closing 'not new hard errors' caveat does not bound the surface."
          },
          {
            "id": "F7",
            "severity": "minor",
            "claim": "Phase 6's labeled name 'Edge Canonical Bridge' is opaque relative to its scope (starter content, contextual help, pattern templates, DoD verification) and risks reader misallocation of effort.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP \u00c2\u00a7'Phase 6: Edge Canonical Bridge' lists 'Three MVP starter examples \u00e2\u20ac\u00a6', 'Contextual help content (\u00c2\u00a725) \u00e2\u20ac\u00a6', 'Initial pattern-template gallery', 'Modeling hints and early semantic-linter warnings \u00e2\u20ac\u00a6', 'Pattern comparison spike (non-shipping investigation, output is a written recommendation)', and DoD verification. None of these are bridging activities between edge-canonical surfaces; the name is inherited from SPEC \u00c2\u00a729 but does not describe the deliverables. A reader scanning the ROADMAP for 'where does help content live?' or 'where do starter examples ship?' will not find Phase 6 by name."
          },
          {
            "id": "F8",
            "severity": "minor",
            "claim": "Phase 1 NOT-in-scope dilutes Phase 3's Turtle-import boundary by carving out an unsized 'minimal Turtle parser' exception with no acceptance criterion.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP Phase 1 NOT-in-scope: 'Full Turtle term extraction and ontology import workflow \u00e2\u20ac\u201d Phase 3 (a minimal Turtle parser is sufficient here for emitter golden-file tests).' Emitter golden-file tests compare *output* Turtle to a committed golden, which does not in general require *parsing* Turtle (the parser is needed only for round-trip Turtle-in tests, which the SPEC does not require in Phase 1). The parenthetical creates a Phase-1 component ('minimal Turtle parser') with no FR anchor and no Phase-1 acceptance criterion, while also signaling that Phase 3 will deliver the 'full' version \u00e2\u20ac\u201d the difference between the two is not defined."
          },
          {
            "id": "F9",
            "severity": "minor",
            "claim": "Cross-Cutting Commitments does not list versioning/migration (\u00c2\u00a710) as a phase-binding invariant, even though every phase that mutates project state must preserve the non-destructive migration policy.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP \u00c2\u00a7'Cross-Cutting Commitments' has six bullets and none of them reference SPEC \u00c2\u00a710 (Versioning and Migration), \u00c2\u00a710.2 (Compatibility Policy), or \u00c2\u00a710.3 (Migration). Legacy v0.2/v0.3 migration is named in Phase 1 scope, but the cross-cutting commitment that future ecm:specVersion bumps remain non-destructive and that snapshot migration (\u00c2\u00a710.5) is preserved across Phase 5 work is not asserted anywhere. Phase 5 introduces new on-disk state (IndexedDB, FSA folders) without an explicit cross-cutting tie to \u00c2\u00a710."
          },
          {
            "id": "F10",
            "severity": "minor",
            "claim": "Phase 2 leaves the FR-U028 (validation report panel) acknowledgement-persistence question unanswered, and no later phase claims it either.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP Phase 2 scope: 'Validation report panel with per-finding acknowledgement (FR-U028, \u00c2\u00a717.5).' SPEC \u00c2\u00a717.5: 'An acknowledged finding remains in the validation report but is visually suppressed in the UI. Acknowledgement is per-finding and per-target \u00e2\u20ac\u201d re-creating the condition produces a new, un-acknowledged finding.' Acknowledgement state therefore must persist in the project document (likely on ecm:validationReports or alongside it) and must survive save/load, which is canonical-shape territory (Phase 1). The ROADMAP does not say where acknowledgement is stored, does not flag it as a Phase-1 VMP-shape concern, and does not reconcile it with OED-303."
          },
          {
            "id": "F11",
            "severity": "minor",
            "claim": "The ROADMAP references IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md as the authoritative location for acceptance criteria and exit gates, but does not include the creation of that document as a precondition or deliverable for any phase.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP line: 'This document is the \"what to build and when.\" Per-task acceptance criteria, exit gates, and falsifiable test conditions live in [IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md](./IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md).' No file IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md is acknowledged elsewhere; no phase lists 'author IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md' as a deliverable; no Phase 1 entry references it. The roadmap therefore depends on an external document whose existence and authorship are unsequenced."
          },
          {
            "id": "F12",
            "severity": "minor",
            "claim": "Phase dependencies are implied by ordering but not stated as a DAG; concurrent execution opportunities and blocking dependencies are not visible.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP enumerates Phases 1\u00e2\u20ac\u201c6 in linear order with no 'depends on' field. Phase 4 (Export and Packaging) requires Phase 1 emitters (Node) and Phase 2 UI shell, but not Phase 3 (import) for the basic flows. Phase 5 (Persistence) requires Phase 2 (UI shell) but not Phase 3 or 4. The ROADMAP's linear presentation hides these independencies, encouraging strict serial execution even where parallel work is possible. SPEC \u00c2\u00a729 has the same linear shape; the ROADMAP is the document that should refine it."
          },
          {
            "id": "F13",
            "severity": "advisory",
            "claim": "The 'Conformance fixture set' decision in Phase 1 is called out as a deferred decision but is not assigned an OED identifier, while every other deferred decision is.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP Phase 1 'Decisions Deferred': 'Conformance fixture set. The exact set of canonical-v0.4 fixtures (\u00c2\u00a721.3) must be agreed before goldens are committed.' All other deferred decisions in the document use the OED-3xx schema (OED-301 through OED-305). Either this is an OED in waiting or it is informal scope-setting; absent an identifier, it cannot be referenced from later artifacts (synthesist outputs, developer change proposals, audit history)."
          },
          {
            "id": "F14",
            "severity": "advisory",
            "claim": "The roadmap does not bind any phase to the SPEC \u00c2\u00a730 risk register, so phase-specific mitigations (Risk 2 \u00e2\u2020\u2019 Phase 3, Risk 4 \u00e2\u2020\u2019 Phase 1, Risk 7/8 \u00e2\u2020\u2019 Phase 1/6) are not tracked as cross-cutting obligations.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP contains no risk register and no per-phase risk acknowledgement. SPEC \u00c2\u00a730 lists nine risks with mitigations; several name specific phases or features (e.g., Risk 2: 'thresholds; virtualized lists; degraded mode; import report; hard 50 MB file limit (\u00c2\u00a712.2)' \u00e2\u20ac\u201d Phase 3; Risk 8: 'CI verifies determinism on every commit (\u00c2\u00a721.4)' \u00e2\u20ac\u201d Phase 1). The roadmap could verify each phase carries its mitigation forward; it does not."
          },
          {
            "id": "F15",
            "severity": "advisory",
            "claim": "Phase 1 says the Project TBox is 'prepended' to Turtle, N-Triples, and semantic JSON-LD exports, but JSON-LD does not have a 'prepend' semantics the way Turtle/N-Triples do.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP Phase 1 scope: 'Project TBox (\u00c2\u00a75.14) bundled with the implementation and prepended to Turtle / N-Triples / semantic JSON-LD exports.' SPEC \u00c2\u00a719 manifest text: 'Project TBox declarations inlined or referenced (\u00c2\u00a719, NFR-014).' For Turtle/N-Triples 'prepend' is well-defined (TBox triples emitted before ABox triples in the same file). For semantic JSON-LD the analogous operation is inclusion of TBox node objects in the @graph or referencing /tbox/project-tbox.ttl. SPEC \u00c2\u00a731 DoD item 4 says 'semantic JSON-LD retains the project root as a typed ICE' \u00e2\u20ac\u201d it does not require 'prepend'. The roadmap's blanket 'prepended' language is imprecise."
          }
        ],
        "summary": "The ROADMAP is structurally aligned with SPEC \u00c2\u00a729 and faithfully translates the realist-anchoring framing into per-phase scope statements. It does, however, contain three load-bearing gaps and several scope-boundary defects that justify revision before Phase 1 starts. (1) The Definition of Done's two-implementation byte-equality requirement (\u00c2\u00a731 item 14, NFR-013) is verified in Phase 6 but never delivered by any phase \u00e2\u20ac\u201d the second implementation has no owner, no phase, and no entry in Cross-Cutting Commitments. (2) Conformance golden files for emitter outputs are simultaneously claimed by Phase 1 (test harness) and Phase 4 (export goldens), and the resolution is not stated. (3) OED-303 (validation report retention) is parked in Phase 3, but it shapes the canonical project document committed in Phase 1, so Phase 1 cannot freeze its golden files without a Phase-3 decision \u00e2\u20ac\u201d a circular dependency. Beyond those: the Cross-Cutting Commitments enumerate six NFRs but silently drop NFR-007 through NFR-012, narrowing the invariant set in a way the SPEC does not authorize; Phase 6 admits 'modeling hints and early semantic-linter warnings beyond the \u00c2\u00a717 validator' without specifying their representation or interaction with \u00c2\u00a717.5 suppression; Phase 5 schedules the IndexedDB adapter alongside an unresolved IndexedDB schema-versioning OED; and the document references an IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md whose authorship is unsequenced.",
        "recommendation": "revise"
      },
      "depends_on": [
        "urn:fnsr:task:002-roadmap-apply"
      ],
      "attempts": 2,
