    {
      "@id": "urn:fnsr:task:004-roadmap-critique",
      "agent": "adversarial-critic",
      "status": "done",
      "inputs": {
        "target": "urn:fnsr:task:003-roadmap-review",
        "mode": "find structural weaknesses in the roadmap, missed risks, mis-ordered phases, or aspirational acceptance language"
      },
      "outputs": {
        "verdicts": [
          {
            "finding_id": "F1",
            "stance": "confirm",
            "rationale": "The overlap is real and the ROADMAP does not resolve it. Phase 1 scope commits a 'golden-file' test harness referencing \u00c2\u00a721.1. Phase 4 scope adds 'Conformance goldens added for every export format, byte-compared in CI (\u00c2\u00a721.1, NFR-013).' Both cite \u00c2\u00a721.1 and both claim golden-file conformance for the Turtle, N-Triples, semantic JSON-LD, Mermaid, and Markdown emitters. Phase 6 adds a third, distinct layer: 'Per-starter committed golden files: project.jsonld, graph.ttl, graph.nt, graph.jsonld, default.mmd, model-summary.md.' The ROADMAP never specifies which fixture inputs drive Phase 1 goldens (\u00c2\u00a721.3 canonical fixtures), which drive Phase 4 goldens, or how they differ. Because Phase 1 is NOT-in-scope for ZIP packaging, Phase 4's only unambiguously new golden artifact is the manifest.jsonld \u00e2\u20ac\u201d but the ROADMAP does not say this; it says 'every export format.'",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP Phase 1 scope: 'Test harness (\u00c2\u00a721.1): \u00e2\u20ac\u00a6 golden-file \u00e2\u20ac\u00a6 conformance.' ROADMAP Phase 4 scope: 'Conformance goldens added for every export format, byte-compared in CI (\u00c2\u00a721.1, NFR-013).' ROADMAP Phase 6 scope: 'Per-starter committed golden files: project.jsonld, graph.ttl, graph.nt, graph.jsonld, default.mmd, model-summary.md.' SPEC \u00c2\u00a721.1: 'Each starter example has committed golden files for project.jsonld, graph.ttl, graph.nt, graph.jsonld, default.mmd, and model-summary.md.' No phase carves out which input fixtures belong to which phase's golden set."
          },
          {
            "finding_id": "F2",
            "stance": "confirm",
            "rationale": "The circular dependency is structurally real. Phase 1 delivers the canonical serializer and the validator (FR-C001), both of which write to ecm:validationReports. Phase 1 golden files will capture a particular state of ecm:validationReports. OED-303, deferred to Phase 3, determines whether subsequent validation runs append to or replace the array. If 'latest only' is chosen in Phase 3, any golden file committed in Phase 1 that records a multi-report state would be invalid; if 'one per save' is chosen, golden files committed assuming an empty or single-entry state would break. The VMP shape is committed in Phase 1 (\u00c2\u00a75.4 example, \u00c2\u00a75.13) but the policy governing array population is deferred three phases later. The ROADMAP does not carve out that Phase 1 golden files will contain an empty ecm:validationReports \u00e2\u20ac\u201d if they did, the dependency would be relaxed.",
            "evidence": "SPEC \u00c2\u00a75.4 example includes 'ecm:validationReports': [] as a required top-level array. SPEC \u00c2\u00a75.13 defines the ValidationReport Object with ecm:findings and ecm:acknowledged. ROADMAP Phase 1 scope includes 'Structural validator producing every \u00c2\u00a717.2 hard error \u00e2\u20ac\u00a6 every \u00c2\u00a717.3 warning, and the \u00c2\u00a717.4 info findings (FR-C001)' \u00e2\u20ac\u201d this populates ecm:validationReports. ROADMAP Phase 3 'Decisions Deferred': 'OED-303 (Validation report retention). Latest only, or one per save? Affects how the import-time validation report integrates with the project's ecm:validationReports array.' The retention policy governs what is in ecm:validationReports at any point in time; Phase 1 golden files capturing validated states will depend on it."
          },
          {
            "finding_id": "F3",
            "stance": "confirm",
            "rationale": "The finding is structurally correct and the evidence is unambiguous. SPEC \u00c2\u00a731 item 14 states 'Two compliant implementations produce byte-identical canonical and derived artifacts for the conformance fixtures.' ROADMAP Phase 6 explicitly targets DoD verification per \u00c2\u00a731, including this item. No phase in the ROADMAP \u00e2\u20ac\u201d neither numbered phase nor Cross-Cutting Commitments \u00e2\u20ac\u201d schedules, scopes, staffs, or names the creation of a second implementation. The Cross-Cutting Commitments' Determinism bullet ('Two compliant implementations produce byte-identical canonical and derived artifacts for the same input') states the normative property but delivers nothing to make it verifiable. Phase 6's DoD verification of item 14 is unexecutable on the ROADMAP as written.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP Phase 6 scope: 'Final v0.4 Definition of Done verification per \u00c2\u00a731: \u00e2\u20ac\u00a6 byte-identical golden suite green across two independent implementations.' SPEC \u00c2\u00a731 item 14: 'Two compliant implementations produce byte-identical canonical and derived artifacts for the conformance fixtures.' ROADMAP Phase 1 through Phase 6 scopes and Cross-Cutting Commitments: no phase creates, staffs, or assigns a second implementation. The Cross-Cutting Commitments Determinism bullet describes the invariant; it does not deliver the second implementation."
          },
          {
            "finding_id": "F4",
            "stance": "confirm",
            "rationale": "The reviewer is correct that NFR-007 through NFR-012 are absent from the Cross-Cutting Commitments. NFR-012 (lossless canonical round-trip per \u00c2\u00a75.3, \u00c2\u00a76.4) is the most critical omission: it constrains every phase that touches the canonical project document and is directly adjacent to the Determinism bullet already present. NFR-007 (no lock-in, open formats) constrains every export-format choice in Phase 4. NFR-011 (performance bounds per \u00c2\u00a714.2/14.3) constrains Phase 3 (50 MB hard limit, 10,000-term threshold) and Phase 5 (large-project persistence). NFR-008, NFR-009, and NFR-010 are UI-surface NFRs that are less obviously cross-cutting, but their absence means Phase 2 could ship without an explicit cross-cutting obligation to expose IRIs and explain semantics. The net effect is that the cross-cutting invariant set is narrower than the SPEC authorizes.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP Cross-Cutting Commitments lists: NFR-014, NFR-001/002, NFR-003/013, NFR-005, NFR-006, NFR-004 \u00e2\u20ac\u201d six bullets covering eight NFRs. SPEC \u00c2\u00a720 NFR table: NFR-007 (no lock-in), NFR-008 (UI explains semantic modeling per \u00c2\u00a725), NFR-009 (UI exposes IRIs, RDF, terms, triples, serializations), NFR-010 (canvas prioritizes understandable modeling), NFR-011 (performance bounds per \u00c2\u00a714.2 and \u00c2\u00a714.3), NFR-012 (lossless canonical round-trip per \u00c2\u00a75.3 and \u00c2\u00a76.4) \u00e2\u20ac\u201d all absent from the ROADMAP's binding invariant set."
          },
          {
            "finding_id": "F5",
            "stance": "confirm",
            "rationale": "The dependency inversion is real. The IndexedDB schema version number, object-store layout, and index structure must be decided before implementation begins; OED-302 is deferred to a decision WITHIN the phase that is simultaneously implementing the adapter. You cannot commit IndexedDB object-store names and their upgrade callbacks without knowing the migration coordination strategy \u00e2\u20ac\u201d the versionchange event handler, the upgrade callback shape, and the keyspace are all determined by the schema versioning decision. The ROADMAP does not contain a gate requiring OED-302 closure before IndexedDB implementation starts.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP Phase 5 scope: 'IndexedDB adapter with lossless canonical-document storage and recent-projects project picker (FR-S003\u00e2\u20ac\u201cFR-S004).' ROADMAP Phase 5 'Decisions Deferred': 'OED-302 (IndexedDB schema versioning). How IndexedDB schema migrations are coordinated with ecm:specVersion bumps.' No ordering constraint between OED-302 resolution and IndexedDB implementation is stated anywhere in Phase 5 or in Cross-Cutting Commitments."
          },
          {
            "finding_id": "F6",
            "stance": "confirm",
            "rationale": "The finding is structurally correct. SPEC \u00c2\u00a717.4 lists exactly three info finding codes (LEGACY_DOCUMENT_MIGRATED, LEGACY_REALIST_ANCHOR_PLACEHOLDER, NORMALIZED_ON_SAVE) \u00e2\u20ac\u201d a closed enumeration. Phase 6 adds 'heuristics surfaced as info findings' with no codes registered, no location in any schema catalog, no indication of whether they appear in ecm:validationReports (\u00c2\u00a75.13), and no interaction specified with \u00c2\u00a717.5 suppression (which is per-finding and per-target). 'Not new hard errors' only clarifies the severity floor; it does not bound the surface. The ValidationReport shape (\u00c2\u00a75.13) includes ecm:code, ecm:severity, ecm:target, and ecm:acknowledged \u00e2\u20ac\u201d all of which new info findings must populate, but Phase 6 specifies none of these.",
            "evidence": "SPEC \u00c2\u00a717.4 Info table: exactly three rows (LEGACY_DOCUMENT_MIGRATED, LEGACY_REALIST_ANCHOR_PLACEHOLDER, NORMALIZED_ON_SAVE). ROADMAP Phase 6 scope: 'Modeling hints and early semantic-linter warnings beyond the \u00c2\u00a717 validator \u00e2\u20ac\u201d heuristics surfaced as info findings, not new hard errors.' SPEC \u00c2\u00a717.5: 'Acknowledgement is per-finding and per-target \u00e2\u20ac\u201d re-creating the condition produces a new, un-acknowledged finding.' SPEC \u00c2\u00a75.13 ValidationReport Object: requires ecm:code, ecm:severity, ecm:target, ecm:acknowledged on each finding. None of these are addressed for Phase 6 heuristic findings."
          },
          {
            "finding_id": "F7",
            "stance": "confirm",
            "rationale": "The label 'Edge Canonical Bridge' is inherited from SPEC \u00c2\u00a729 and is equally opaque there. The ROADMAP does not rename it to better describe its actual deliverables (starter examples, contextual help, pattern templates, DoD verification, pattern comparison spike). A reader scanning the ROADMAP for 'where do starter examples ship?' will not find Phase 6 by name. This is a structural discoverability defect, not a stylistic one \u00e2\u20ac\u201d the phase name is the primary navigation anchor in a multi-phase document. The reviewer's severity of 'minor' is correct given the finding is self-contained and does not invalidate any other phase's scope.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP Phase 6 heading: 'Phase 6: Edge Canonical Bridge.' Phase 6 scope items: starter examples, contextual help content, initial pattern-template gallery, modeling hints and semantic-linter warnings, pattern comparison spike (non-shipping), DoD verification. None of these are 'bridging' activities. SPEC \u00c2\u00a729 Phase 6: 'starter examples (MVP and advanced sets); pattern templates (initial gallery); modeling hints; early semantic linter warnings; pattern comparison spike.' The label is not derived from the deliverables in either document."
          },
          {
            "finding_id": "F8",
            "stance": "confirm",
            "rationale": "The reviewer's core technical claim is correct: emitter golden-file tests compare generated output (a Turtle string) to a committed file \u00e2\u20ac\u201d they do not require a Turtle parser. The \u00c2\u00a717.6 validity check ('Generated Turtle and N-Triples must parse cleanly under N3.js with no errors') IS the case that would require a parser, and it is explicitly Phase 4 scope ('Generated-artifact validity check: Turtle and N-Triples parse cleanly under N3.js with no errors (\u00c2\u00a717.6)'). Phase 1's parenthetical ('a minimal Turtle parser is sufficient here for emitter golden-file tests') is therefore technically wrong \u00e2\u20ac\u201d it justifies a Phase-1 component against a test type that doesn't need it. This creates a scoped-but-unanchored deliverable with no FR reference and no acceptance criterion.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP Phase 1 NOT-in-scope: 'Full Turtle term extraction and ontology import workflow \u00e2\u20ac\u201d Phase 3 (a minimal Turtle parser is sufficient here for emitter golden-file tests).' ROADMAP Phase 4 scope: 'Generated-artifact validity check: Turtle and N-Triples parse cleanly under N3.js with no errors (\u00c2\u00a717.6).' SPEC \u00c2\u00a717.6: 'Generated Turtle and N-Triples must parse cleanly under N3.js with no errors. This is a build-time conformance requirement validated by tests (\u00c2\u00a721), not a runtime self-check.' Emitter golden-file tests require only: emit Turtle, compare byte-to-committed-golden \u00e2\u20ac\u201d no parse step."
          },
          {
            "finding_id": "F9",
            "stance": "confirm",
            "rationale": "The reviewer is correct. \u00c2\u00a710 (Versioning and Migration) defines a cross-cutting invariant \u00e2\u20ac\u201d non-destructive migration, compatibility policy, ecm:specVersion enforcement \u00e2\u20ac\u201d that applies to every phase that touches canonical project state. Phase 5 introduces two new on-disk storage surfaces (IndexedDB and FSA folders), each of which must coordinate with ecm:specVersion via a migration function. Neither the Cross-Cutting Commitments nor Phase 5 explicitly binds this work to \u00c2\u00a710.2/\u00c2\u00a710.3/\u00c2\u00a710.5. Phase 6's starter examples also introduce new canonical-v0.4 project files that must be migrable per the policy. The absence means future ecm:specVersion bumps have no mandated cross-cutting obligation in the ROADMAP.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP Cross-Cutting Commitments: six bullets; none reference SPEC \u00c2\u00a710 (Versioning and Migration), \u00c2\u00a710.2 (Compatibility Policy), \u00c2\u00a710.3 (Migration), or \u00c2\u00a710.5 (Snapshot Migration). SPEC \u00c2\u00a710.3: 'Migration is non-destructive: the original document is preserved on disk under project.jsonld.pre-migration.<sourceVersion> unless the caller opts out.' ROADMAP Phase 5 scope introduces IndexedDB adapter and FSA folder sync without an explicit \u00c2\u00a710 cross-reference. ROADMAP Phase 1 scope mentions 'Legacy migration: v0.2 \u00e2\u2020\u2019 v0.3 \u00e2\u2020\u2019 v0.4 on load' in Phase 1 only."
          },
          {
            "finding_id": "F10",
            "stance": "confirm",
            "rationale": "The acknowledgement persistence gap is real. SPEC \u00c2\u00a75.13 defines ecm:acknowledged on each ValidationFinding \u00e2\u20ac\u201d it IS part of the VMP shape, so Phase 1 establishes the schema. But Phase 2 introduces the UI interaction for acknowledgement (FR-U028) without specifying how acknowledged state is written back to ecm:validationReports in the canonical document and what happens to it on save/reload. The interaction with OED-303 is significant: if 'latest only' retention is chosen, a user who acknowledged a finding will lose that acknowledgement when the report is replaced on next save. The ROADMAP does not say this is a known limitation or that it must be resolved before Phase 3 closes OED-303.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP Phase 2 scope: 'Validation report panel with per-finding acknowledgement (FR-U028, \u00c2\u00a717.5).' SPEC \u00c2\u00a717.5: 'An acknowledged finding remains in the validation report but is visually suppressed in the UI. Acknowledgement is per-finding and per-target \u00e2\u20ac\u201d re-creating the condition produces a new, un-acknowledged finding.' SPEC \u00c2\u00a75.13 ValidationFinding: 'ecm:acknowledged': false. SPEC \u00c2\u00a76.2 Editor Layer: 'ecm:ValidationReport, ecm:ValidationFinding' and 'ecm:acknowledged' are Editor Layer fields that persist in canonical project document. OED-303 (Phase 3): determines whether reports are replaced or appended \u00e2\u20ac\u201d directly affects acknowledged-finding persistence."
          },
          {
            "finding_id": "F11",
            "stance": "confirm",
            "rationale": "The dangling reference is confirmed. The ROADMAP's opening line delegates acceptance criteria and exit gates to IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md. No phase lists authoring IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md as a deliverable. No cross-cutting commitment asserts it must exist before Phase 1 starts. This means per-task acceptance criteria are structurally unsequenced \u00e2\u20ac\u201d Phase 1 could begin with only the high-level scope bullets in the ROADMAP as its definition of done, which the reviewer correctly identifies as a structural gap.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP line 7: 'This document is the \"what to build and when.\" Per-task acceptance criteria, exit gates, and falsifiable test conditions live in IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md.' Searching all six phase scopes, NOT-in-scope lists, and Decisions Deferred sections: no phase lists 'author IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md' as a deliverable. Cross-Cutting Commitments: no mention of IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md. The file is referenced but not created."
          },
          {
            "finding_id": "F12",
            "stance": "confirm",
            "rationale": "The linear ordering genuinely obscures valid concurrency opportunities. Phase 4 (Export and Packaging) requires Phase 1 emitters and Phase 2 browser UI shell, but not Phase 3 (Ontology Import) \u00e2\u20ac\u201d the Phase 4 scope contains no import-dependent features. Phase 5 (Local Persistence Adapters) requires Phase 2 (browser UI) but is independent of Phase 3 and Phase 4 for most of its scope (persistence adapters wrap the canonical document; they don't require export-format browser flows or ontology import). The ROADMAP presents these as sequentially dependent, inflating the critical path. The SPEC \u00c2\u00a729 has the same linear shape, so the ROADMAP missed an opportunity to refine it.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP Phase 4 scope: Turtle/N-Triples/JSON-LD/Mermaid/Markdown download flows, ZIP packaging, export manifest \u00e2\u20ac\u201d none depends on Phase 3's Turtle import. ROADMAP Phase 5 scope: in-memory adapter, file save/load adapter, IndexedDB adapter, FSA integration, BroadcastChannel, Snapshots \u00e2\u20ac\u201d all depend on canonical project document (Phase 1) and browser UI shell (Phase 2); none depends on Phase 3 or Phase 4 for their core function. No 'depends_on' field or DAG annotation exists anywhere in the ROADMAP."
          },
          {
            "finding_id": "F13",
            "stance": "confirm",
            "rationale": "The missing OED identifier is confirmed. Every other deferred decision in the ROADMAP carries an OED-3xx label (OED-301 through OED-305). The 'Conformance fixture set' in Phase 1 deferred decisions is an informal entry with no machine-referenceable identifier. Because downstream artifacts (synthesist documents, developer change proposals, Barcode audit history) cross-reference decisions by OED identifier, this decision cannot be reliably tracked, closed, or audited.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP Phase 1 'Decisions Deferred': 'Conformance fixture set. The exact set of canonical-v0.4 fixtures (\u00c2\u00a721.3) must be agreed before goldens are committed.' All other deferred decisions: 'OED-301 (Mermaid edge label policy)', 'OED-302 (IndexedDB schema versioning)', 'OED-303 (Validation report retention)', 'OED-304 (ZIP manifest signing)', 'OED-305 (Help-content localization mechanism)' \u00e2\u20ac\u201d each has a structured identifier. 'Conformance fixture set' does not."
          },
          {
            "finding_id": "F14",
            "stance": "confirm",
            "rationale": "The reviewer correctly identifies that SPEC \u00c2\u00a730's nine risks contain phase-specific mitigations that the ROADMAP never cross-references. Risk 2 (browser crashes on large ontologies) maps to Phase 3 mitigations (named-term extraction, 50 MB limit, degraded mode). Risk 4 (JSON-LD complexity slows MVP) maps to Phase 1 mitigations (constrained VMP, bundled context). Risk 7 (two implementations diverge) maps to Phase 1 and Phase 6. Risk 8 (determinism claims overpromise) maps to Phase 1 (CI job per \u00c2\u00a721.4). Without per-phase risk acknowledgements in the ROADMAP, a phase can declare itself done without verifying its mitigations are implemented.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP: no risk register, no per-phase risk cross-reference. SPEC \u00c2\u00a730 Risk 2 mitigation: 'named-term extraction only; thresholds; virtualized lists; degraded mode; import report; hard 50 MB file limit (\u00c2\u00a712.2)' \u00e2\u20ac\u201d Phase 3 features. Risk 4 mitigation: 'constrained VMP profile; bundled local context; no remote context resolution' \u00e2\u20ac\u201d Phase 1 commitments. Risk 7 mitigation: 'VMP normative profile (\u00c2\u00a75); canonical serializer (\u00c2\u00a75.3); golden-file conformance suite (\u00c2\u00a721.1); explicit byte-identity requirement (NFR-013)' \u00e2\u20ac\u201d Phase 1 and Phase 6. None of these cross-references appear in the ROADMAP."
          },
          {
            "finding_id": "F15",
            "stance": "extend",
            "rationale": "The reviewer correctly identifies semantic imprecision in 'prepended' for JSON-LD, but the evidence cited (ROADMAP Phase 1 scope vs. SPEC \u00c2\u00a731 DoD item 4) does not create the contradiction claimed. The stronger issue is that SPEC \u00c2\u00a76.3 step 5 itself uses 'Prepend the Project TBox declarations from \u00c2\u00a75.14 to the resulting RDF graph' for the semantic JSON-LD export algorithm, and SPEC \u00c2\u00a731 DoD item 2 says 'prepended to all semantic exports.' The ROADMAP is faithfully reproducing the SPEC's own imprecise language. The finding is valid \u00e2\u20ac\u201d file-level prepend (Turtle/N-Triples) is operationally different from graph-level TBox node insertion (JSON-LD) \u00e2\u20ac\u201d but it is a SPEC defect that the ROADMAP inherits, not a ROADMAP-specific deviation. The advisory severity is appropriate.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP Phase 1 scope: 'Project TBox (\u00c2\u00a75.14) bundled with the implementation and prepended to Turtle / N-Triples / semantic JSON-LD exports.' SPEC \u00c2\u00a76.3 step 5: 'Prepend the Project TBox declarations from \u00c2\u00a75.14 to the resulting RDF graph.' SPEC \u00c2\u00a731 DoD item 2: 'The Project TBox (\u00c2\u00a75.14) is bundled with the implementation and prepended to all semantic exports.' SPEC \u00c2\u00a75.14 notes: 'The Turtle and N-Triples exports prepend the TBox declarations so the resulting RDF graph is self-contained' \u00e2\u20ac\u201d this language distinguishes Turtle/N-Triples but \u00c2\u00a76.3 and \u00c2\u00a731 both apply 'prepend' to JSON-LD as well. The ROADMAP is not introducing new imprecision."
          }
        ],
        "missed_findings": [
          {
            "id": "M1",
            "severity": "major",
            "claim": "Phase 1 CLI scope directly contradicts Phase 1 NOT-in-scope on two commands: 'import-ontology' (whose implementation is Phase 3) and 'export (all formats)' which per \u00c2\u00a723 includes '--format zip' (whose implementation is Phase 4). The ROADMAP gives no reconciliation \u00e2\u20ac\u201d no stub behavior, no error code, no deferred command registration.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP Phase 1 scope: 'Node CLI surface (\u00c2\u00a723): validate, export (all formats), import-ontology, migrate, refactor-iri, with deterministic flags --seed / --clock, exit codes 0\u00e2\u20ac\u201c4.' ROADMAP Phase 1 NOT-in-scope: 'Full Turtle term extraction and ontology import workflow \u00e2\u20ac\u201d Phase 3.' ROADMAP Phase 1 NOT-in-scope: 'ZIP packaging \u00e2\u20ac\u201d Phase 4.' SPEC \u00c2\u00a723 CLI surface: 'node index.js import-ontology project.jsonld ontology.ttl --out updated-project.jsonld' and 'node index.js export project.jsonld --format zip --out package.zip.' If 'export (all formats)' in Phase 1 means all formats from \u00c2\u00a723, it includes ZIP. If 'import-ontology' is a Phase 1 CLI command, what does it do when the underlying Turtle term extractor is Phase 3? No answer exists in the ROADMAP. Phase 1 acceptance criteria derived from these scope lines are contradictory."
          },
          {
            "id": "M2",
            "severity": "major",
            "claim": "The ROADMAP creates golden-file artifacts across three phases (Phase 1 test harness goldens, Phase 4 export-format conformance goldens, Phase 6 per-starter goldens) but provides no cross-phase governance for what happens when later phases change canonical output shape. Phase 3's OED-303 decision changes ecm:validationReports population; Phase 4 adds manifest entries and changes Turtle/N-Triples to include the TBox explicitly; Phase 5 may affect snapshot serialization format. Each of these can invalidate golden files committed in an earlier phase. SPEC \u00c2\u00a721.1 says 'Updating golden files requires explicit human review (the diff goes through PR)' \u00e2\u20ac\u201d but no phase owns this update work, and no cross-cutting commitment binds phases to keep earlier phases' golden suites green.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP Phase 1 scope: 'Test harness (\u00c2\u00a721.1): \u00e2\u20ac\u00a6 golden-file \u00e2\u20ac\u00a6 conformance.' ROADMAP Phase 4 scope: 'Conformance goldens added for every export format, byte-compared in CI (\u00c2\u00a721.1, NFR-013).' ROADMAP Phase 6 scope: 'Per-starter committed golden files: project.jsonld, graph.ttl, graph.nt, graph.jsonld, default.mmd, model-summary.md.' SPEC \u00c2\u00a721.1: 'Updating golden files requires explicit human review (the diff goes through PR). Golden files are byte-compared on every CI run.' ROADMAP Phase 3 'Decisions Deferred': OED-303 directly affects ecm:validationReports content, which is in every canonical project golden file. No phase has a scope line reading 'update Phase N golden files to reflect Phase M changes.' The ROADMAP does not establish which team or phase owns golden-file migration when upstream canonical output shape changes."
          },
          {
            "id": "M3",
            "severity": "major",
            "claim": "Phase 5 is the most implementation-complex phase in the ROADMAP (covering in-memory adapter, file adapter, IndexedDB adapter, FSA three-tier hybrid with OPFS and IndexedDB, BroadcastChannel coordination, Snapshot externalization with migration, stale-save detection, Safari/Firefox fallback, Node advisory locking, audit log with rotation, and permission lifecycle management) yet its 'Decisions Deferred' section lists only OED-302. The FSA integration alone involves multiple unresolved design choices \u00e2\u20ac\u201d OPFS vs. IndexedDB caching policy for derived artifacts, the BroadcastChannel coordination protocol for concurrent tabs, permission grant/revoke behavior when the user revokes mid-session, the audit-log rotation trigger and format \u00e2\u20ac\u201d none of which are enumerated as deferred decisions or flagged as delivery risks. Phase 5 will encounter implementation-blocking decisions that do not appear anywhere in the ROADMAP's decision surface.",
            "evidence": "ROADMAP Phase 5 scope (partial): 'File System Access API integration per \u00c2\u00a715.9 (FR-S006): three-tier hybrid (FSA system of record, OPFS derived caches, IndexedDB indexes + persisted FileSystemDirectoryHandle), the recommended on-disk layout (\u00c2\u00a715.9.2), atomic writes, NFC + Windows-reserved-name path sanitization, permission lifecycle (granted/prompt/denied + reconnect UX), adoption semantics for pre-existing app folders, audit log with rotation, lock-ordered per-path concurrency.' ROADMAP Phase 5 'Decisions Deferred': 'OED-302 (IndexedDB schema versioning). How IndexedDB schema migrations are coordinated with ecm:specVersion bumps.' SPEC \u00c2\u00a730 risk register: no risk specific to Phase 5 FSA integration. The ratio of scope complexity to enumerated open decisions (~15 sub-features, 1 OED) is not credible."
          }
        ],
        "overall_verdict": "reviewer_under_rigorous",
        "summary": "The reviewer produced 15 well-evidenced findings \u00e2\u20ac\u201d 14 of which are confirmed and one extended. The structural identification of Phase 1/4 golden-file overlap (F1), the OED-303 circular dependency (F2), the missing second implementation (F3), the under-enumerated Cross-Cutting Commitments (F4), and the inverted IndexedDB schema decision (F5) are all sound and correctly severity-rated. F15 is extended rather than confirmed outright: the ROADMAP's 'prepended to \u00e2\u20ac\u00a6 semantic JSON-LD' language faithfully reproduces SPEC \u00c2\u00a76.3 step 5 and \u00c2\u00a731 DoD item 2, making it a spec defect the ROADMAP inherits, not a ROADMAP-specific deviation. The reviewer missed three major structural problems: (M1) Phase 1's CLI scope explicitly includes 'import-ontology' and 'export (all formats)' \u00e2\u20ac\u201d which per \u00c2\u00a723 covers ZIP \u00e2\u20ac\u201d while Phase 1 NOT-in-scope rules out both the ontology import implementation (Phase 3) and ZIP packaging (Phase 4), creating a direct intra-Phase-1 self-contradiction; (M2) no cross-phase governance exists for golden-file evolution when later phases change the canonical output shape that Phase 1 golden files captured; and (M3) Phase 5's decision surface is drastically under-enumerated relative to its scope \u00e2\u20ac\u201d the FSA three-tier hybrid alone introduces multiple unresolved design choices not surfaced as OEDs. M1 is the most acute: it makes Phase 1 acceptance criteria internally inconsistent and is a blocking defect."
      },
