            "consensus": "critic_only",
            "resolution": "accept_critic",
            "severity": "major",
            "rationale": "Phase 1 scope states: 'Node CLI surface (\u00c2\u00a723): validate, export (all formats), import-ontology, migrate, refactor-iri, with deterministic flags --seed / --clock, exit codes 0\u00e2\u20ac\u201c4.' Phase 1 NOT-in-scope simultaneously states: 'Full Turtle term extraction and ontology import workflow \u00e2\u20ac\u201d Phase 3' and 'ZIP packaging \u00e2\u20ac\u201d Phase 4.' Per SPEC \u00c2\u00a723, 'export (all formats)' includes '--format zip' and 'import-ontology' invokes the Turtle term extractor. If Phase 1 registers these CLI commands but their underlying implementations are Phase 3/4 deliverables, the ROADMAP provides no stub behavior, no error code, no deferred command registration strategy, and no acceptance criterion governing command availability. Phase 1 acceptance criteria derived from the CLI scope line are internally inconsistent. The critic identified this as the most acute finding in the document \u00e2\u20ac\u201d it is an intra-Phase-1 self-contradiction, not a cross-phase disagreement. The reviewer did not surface it. The source artifact confirms all cited lines at lines 41, 46\u00e2\u20ac\u201c47.",
            "trace": {
              "critic_missed_id": "M1"
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "I17",
            "title": "No cross-phase governance exists for golden-file evolution when later phases change the canonical output shape that earlier phases' golden files captured",
            "consensus": "critic_only",
            "resolution": "accept_critic",
            "severity": "major",
            "rationale": "Golden files are committed across three phases (Phase 1 test harness goldens, Phase 4 export-format conformance goldens, Phase 6 per-starter goldens) but no phase owns the work of updating earlier phases' golden files when later phases change canonical output shape. Phase 3's OED-303 decision changes ecm:validationReports population; Phase 4 adds manifest entries and changes Turtle/N-Triples to include the TBox explicitly; Phase 5 may affect snapshot serialization format. Each of these can invalidate golden files committed in an earlier phase. SPEC \u00c2\u00a721.1 requires that 'Updating golden files requires explicit human review (the diff goes through PR)' \u00e2\u20ac\u201d but no phase has a scope line reading 'update Phase N golden files to reflect Phase M changes,' and no cross-cutting commitment binds phases to keep earlier phases' golden suites green. This issue is distinct from I1: I1 concerns which phase first commits goldens for a given format; I17 concerns what happens when a later-phase canonical output change invalidates earlier committed goldens with no assigned owner. The reviewer did not surface this governance gap.",
            "trace": {
              "critic_missed_id": "M2"
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "I18",
            "title": "Phase 5's decision surface is drastically under-enumerated relative to its implementation scope; multiple FSA sub-decisions are not registered as OEDs",
            "consensus": "critic_only",
            "resolution": "accept_critic",
            "severity": "major",
            "rationale": "Phase 5 is the most implementation-complex phase in the ROADMAP (covering in-memory adapter, file adapter, IndexedDB adapter, FSA three-tier hybrid with OPFS and IndexedDB, BroadcastChannel coordination, snapshot externalization with migration, stale-save detection, Safari/Firefox fallback, Node advisory locking, audit log with rotation, and permission lifecycle management \u00e2\u20ac\u201d approximately 15 named sub-features) yet its Decisions Deferred section lists only OED-302. The FSA integration alone introduces multiple unresolved design choices not surfaced as OEDs: OPFS vs. IndexedDB caching policy for derived artifacts; BroadcastChannel coordination protocol for concurrent tabs; permission grant/revoke behavior when the user revokes mid-session; audit-log rotation trigger and format. The ratio of scope complexity to enumerated open decisions (~15 sub-features, 1 OED) is not credible and means implementation-blocking decisions will be encountered during Phase 5 with no prior decision record, no Barcode-trackable OED closure requirement, and no cross-cutting risk acknowledgement. The reviewer did not surface this gap. The source artifact confirms Phase 5 scope at lines 153\u00e2\u20ac\u201c162 and the single deferred decision at line 172.",
            "trace": {
              "critic_missed_id": "M3"
            }
          }
        ],
        "recommendation": "revise",
        "outstanding_questions": [
          "Is a second GraphWrite implementation in scope for any team, workstream, or external party? If not, SPEC \u00c2\u00a731 item 14 must be relaxed or excised before Phase 6 DoD verification can be executed as written.",
          "What is the intended Phase 1 behavior of CLI commands 'import-ontology' and 'export --format zip', given that their underlying implementations are Phase 3 and Phase 4 deliverables respectively? Stub with a documented exit code? Unregistered until their phase ships? An answer is required before Phase 1 acceptance criteria can be made non-contradictory.",
          "Should OED-303 (validation report retention) be elevated from Phase 3 to Phase 1 to unblock Phase 1 golden-file commits? Or will Phase 1 golden files explicitly capture an empty ecm:validationReports array, with that constraint documented as a temporary assumption pending OED-303 resolution?",
          "What is the exact input fixture set for Phase 1 golden files versus Phase 4 golden files? The 'Conformance fixture set' deferred decision in Phase 1 must be resolved and assigned an OED identifier before either phase can commit goldens; the current informal entry cannot be tracked or closed in the Barcode audit trail.",
          "Which Phase 5 FSA sub-decisions (OPFS/IndexedDB caching policy, BroadcastChannel coordination protocol, mid-session permission revocation behavior, audit-log rotation policy) require formal OED entries, and who is responsible for authoring and closing them before Phase 5 implementation begins?"
        ],
        "summary": "The reviewer produced 15 well-evidenced findings (F1\u00e2\u20ac\u201cF15) across major, minor, and advisory severity levels. The adversarial critic confirmed all 15 without refuting any, extended 4 (F1, F8, F12, F15) with material scope widening or sharpened argumentation, and surfaced 3 additional major findings the reviewer missed (M1, M2, M3). No finding was refuted; no escalation is required. The synthesis produces 18 issues: 9 major (I1\u00e2\u20ac\u201cI6, I16\u00e2\u20ac\u201cI18), 6 minor (I7\u00e2\u20ac\u201cI12), and 3 advisory (I13\u00e2\u20ac\u201cI15), all un-refuted. The most critical cluster: (1) Phase 1's CLI scope is internally self-contradictory \u00e2\u20ac\u201d 'import-ontology' and 'export (all formats)' are declared Phase 1 commands while their implementations are Phase 3 and Phase 4 deliverables, with no stub, error code, or deferred registration strategy (I16/M1 \u00e2\u20ac\u201d the most acute finding); (2) Phase 6 cannot execute DoD \u00c2\u00a731 item 14 because no phase in the ROADMAP delivers or even names a second implementation (I3/F3); (3) Phase 1 golden files cannot be finalized without OED-303 resolution, but OED-303 is deferred to Phase 3, creating a circular dependency on Phase 1's primary deliverable (I2/F2); (4) golden-file governance across phases is entirely absent \u00e2\u20ac\u201d no phase owns updating earlier phases' golden files when later-phase canonical output changes invalidate them (I17/M2); (5) Phase 5's decision surface lists one OED against approximately fifteen named sub-features, guaranteeing that implementation-blocking decisions will be encountered without prior decision records (I18/M3). Structural defects compound the delivery risk: the Cross-Cutting Commitments silently drop NFR-007 through NFR-012 (I4/F4) and SPEC \u00c2\u00a710 versioning obligations (I9/F9); IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md \u00e2\u20ac\u201d the only document that would make Phase 1 acceptance criteria falsifiable \u00e2\u20ac\u201d is referenced but unsequenced as a deliverable (I11/F11); and the 'Conformance fixture set' deferred decision in Phase 1 has no OED identifier and therefore cannot be tracked or closed in the Barcode audit trail (I13/F13). The ROADMAP requires substantive revision before Phase 1 can begin with consistent, falsifiable, non-contradictory acceptance criteria."
      },
