            "source": "CLAUDE.md"
          }
        ],
        "bankings": [
          {
            "id": "B1",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "Deployment-scope bifurcation for test-only devDependencies: the developer placed the N3.js import exclusively in the test file (tests/tbox-bundle.test.ts) while src/tbox/index.ts has zero imports and embeds the tested artifact as a pure string constant. This pattern prevents devDependency leakage into the production build while still allowing the devDep to exercise the artifact under test. The bifurcation is self-enforcing: tsconfig.json excludes tests/ from the production compile target, so even if a maintainer accidentally added an n3 import to src/, the build would fail on missing runtime dependency. This pattern is directly applicable to any future task that introduces a format-parsing devDep (e.g., a JSON-LD library at task 1.5's semantic-export boundary)."
          },
          {
            "id": "B2",
            "category": "methodology-refinement-candidate",
            "content": "The purity checker (scripts/ensure-kernel-purity.ts) is hardcoded to scan dist-tests/src/kernel/ only. src/tbox/ is now a second pure-utility module outside the checked surface: today it has zero imports and is inert, but there is no mechanical enforcement ensuring it stays that way. As Phase 1 adds more kernel-adjacent modules (candidates include src/schema/, src/ontology/, or other pure utility bundles), the gap between the 'kernel-adjacent pure' design intent and the purity enforcement mechanism will widen. A future refinement would generalize ensure-kernel-purity.ts to accept a configurable set of monitored directories (or a 'pure-surface' glob), or introduce a second purity check targeting the broader src/ surface with the same forbidden-pattern set. This refinement is low-urgency while src/tbox/ has no imports, but becomes load-bearing if the module grows or is replicated."
          },
          {
            "id": "B3",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "Duck-type interface pattern for type-safe N3.js use under moduleResolution NodeNext without @types/n3: the developer declared minimal local interfaces (RdfTerm { value: string }, RdfQuad { subject, predicate, object }) and used an 'as RdfQuad[]' cast on the parser output. This avoids a second devDep (@types/n3) and bypasses any N3 type-resolution issues under strict+skipLibCheck, while still providing nominal type safety within the test. The pattern is appropriate for test utilities that use a devDep for its runtime behavior (parse correctness, quad emission) rather than for deep type-system integration. Future test authors importing single-purpose devDeps for runtime verification (not type composition) can apply this pattern to avoid dependency proliferation."
          }
        ]
      },
