        "bankings": [
          {
            "id": "B1",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "Scope-splitting large-scope Phase 1 validator tasks by finding-category group (A: project-level structural errors, B: cross-reference dangling errors, C: warnings + info codes) is an effective decomposition pattern when the full implementation surface would exceed single-dispatch output budget limits. The developer's follow-up chain A/B/C structure \u00e2\u20ac\u201d naming each deferred code explicitly in TODO comments, assigning codes to task-specific deferrals (STALE_SAVE_TARGET \u00e2\u2020\u2019 task 5.7; LEGACY_* \u00e2\u2020\u2019 task 1.9; NORMALIZED_ON_SAVE \u00e2\u2020\u2019 task 1.10) and phase deferrals (LARGE_IMPORT \u00e2\u2020\u2019 Phase 3), and producing a complete accounting of all 26 SPEC-declared codes across chains \u00e2\u20ac\u201d constitutes a reusable handoff pattern for future large-scope Phase 1 tasks. The key enabler is a central codes.ts enumeration file that gives subsequent dispatches a stable target to import without re-deriving the full code set."
          },
          {
            "id": "B2",
            "category": "discipline-correction",
            "content": "When task-level scope_constraints resolve an architectural question that reconnaissance explicitly flagged as needing an ADR (here: src/validate/ vs src/kernel/ module placement, and Phase-3-scoped check handling in Phase 1), an ADR should still be authored as part of the developer dispatch or as a ratification condition \u00e2\u20ac\u201d not deferred silently. In this case, the placement decision is traceable through the task inputs scope_constraints, but it does not appear in DECISIONS.md. Future developers editing or extending src/validate/ will not find the rationale for why this module is outside the purity checker's scope, why it may import from src/tbox/ without constraint, or why STALE_SAVE_TARGET was placed at the persistence adapter rather than the kernel. The pattern to establish: when task inputs resolve an architectural question flagged by recon as ADR-worthy, the developer dispatch should propose the ADR or the ratification ruling should condition ratification on ADR creation. This dispatch ratifies without that condition because the decision is stable and traceable, but the discipline gap should not recur."
          },
          {
            "id": "B3",
            "category": "methodology-refinement-candidate",
            "content": "The kernel purity checker (ensure-kernel-purity.ts) scans only src/kernel/, creating a structural enforcement blind spot for new pure-by-design modules like src/validate/ and src/tbox/. Both modules are currently pure by discipline and code-comment assertion, but there is no tool-enforced gate analogous to the kernel purity check. As Phase 1 continues to produce new peer modules (src/migrate/, src/emitter/, etc.), the gap between tool-enforced purity (Layer 0 kernel) and discipline-only purity (all other pure-by-design modules) will widen. A methodology refinement candidate: expand the purity checker or introduce a parallel check for named pure-by-design non-kernel modules, parameterized by directory. This is a Phase 1 exit gate candidate for the purity enforcement surface, not a blocker for this dispatch."
          }
        ]
      },
