        "bankings": [
          {
            "id": "B1",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "When reconnaissance reveals that a downstream task's core computation is already substantially complete in an upstream module (here, projectSemantic() fully implements FR-C005 before the emitters task was dispatched), the developer correctly identifies this and proposes a thin-wrapper Chain 2 rather than reimplementing. This pattern \u00e2\u20ac\u201d reconnaissance exposes 'already substantially done' signals that calibrate developer scope \u00e2\u20ac\u201d is a load-bearing use of the reconnaissance step that goes beyond just gap detection. It suggests adding an explicit 'already_implemented' or 'scope_reduction' signal category to reconnaissance output schema so operators can see at a glance which functional requirements require net-new work vs thin wiring."
          },
          {
            "id": "B2",
            "category": "methodology-refinement-candidate",
            "content": "The 3-chain scope split (Chain 1: N3-based emitters + narration; Chain 2: projectSemantic wrapper; Chain 3: Mermaid stub + Markdown hand-rolled) clusters emitters by their external-library dependency type and implementation complexity tier. This 'cluster-by-dependency' scope-split strategy produces coherent atomic commits, avoids token-limit issues on large multi-format tasks, and creates clear hand-off points with explicitly stubbed acceptance criteria. Candidate for PLAYBOOK documentation as the recommended strategy when a task covers N \u00e2\u2030\u00a5 3 output formats with heterogeneous library footprints."
          },
          {
            "id": "B3",
            "category": "discipline-correction",
            "content": "CLAUDE.md \u00c2\u00a76 states 'MUST NOT add runtime dependencies to GraphWrite package.json without explicit Human Orchestrator approval.' This constraint correctly gates additions but is silent on devDependency-to-dependency reclassification. The emitters proposal places n3 imports in production source files (src/emit/) while n3 remains a devDependency, creating a latent deployment defect (production npm install would lack n3). The discipline should be extended: any change to package.json that increases the production runtime footprint \u00e2\u20ac\u201d whether an addition or a reclassification \u00e2\u20ac\u201d requires explicit Human Orchestrator approval. The developer correctly surfaces this as an open operator-decision question rather than silently reclassifying, which is the right behavior under the current constraint; the correction is at the constraint-definition level."
          }
        ]
      },
