        "bankings": [
          {
            "id": "B1",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "TypeScript's `ReturnType<typeof fn>` utility applied to factory functions with a generic-last overload resolves to the constraint type (e.g., `n3.BaseQuad`) rather than the default concrete type (e.g., `n3.Quad`), because TypeScript picks the constraint bound of the last overload's type parameter when inferring `ReturnType<>`. The robust fix pattern is to abandon `ReturnType<>` annotations on such factory calls and instead import the concrete class explicitly (e.g., `import { Quad } from 'n3'`) and annotate with `Quad[]` directly. This pattern will recur with any typed-factory library that exposes generic-last overloads (n3, rdfjs, and similar); `ReturnType<>` is not safe to use against overloaded factory functions where the last overload is generic."
          },
          {
            "id": "B2",
            "category": "methodology-refinement-candidate",
            "content": "Change proposals that bundle pure type-annotation corrections (C1/C2/C5 here \u00e2\u20ac\u201d import and return-type annotation changes only) with runtime-guard additions (C3/C4 \u00e2\u20ac\u201d new conditional branching) create ratification scope ambiguity because the two categories have different editorial/substantive profiles. The annotation-only changes would qualify as editorial and could use the faster editorial chain; the guard additions are substantive. Future developer proposals for type-correctness fixes would benefit from structuring annotation-only changes and runtime-guard additions as separate logical groups with separate rationales, enabling the architect to issue split editorial/substantive classifications and route each through the appropriate chain. At current task volume this is advisory; it becomes load-bearing when chain throughput is a constraint."
          }
        ]
      },
