        ],
        "bankings": [
          {
            "id": "B1",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "The 'pragmatic-default-pending-ADR' implementation pattern: when SPEC leaves a deterministic constant underspecified (here: the UUIDv5 namespace UUID per \u00c2\u00a79.3) and the AC that would require byte-identical frozen output is itself deferred (AC4 per OED-313), the developer implements with a documented default (RFC 4122 URL namespace), flags the open question in an inline NOTE comment, and records the ADR prerequisite in open_questions output. This allows forward progress on the in-scope ACs (AC1\u00e2\u20ac\u201cAC3) without blocking on spec completion for the deferred AC (AC4). The sequencing is: implement-with-documented-default \u00e2\u2020\u2019 ratify AC1\u00e2\u20ac\u201cAC3 \u00e2\u2020\u2019 formalize ADR before un-deferring AC4. This pattern is reusable whenever an AC-gated constant is underspecified and the AC that freezes the constant is itself deferred."
          },
          {
            "id": "B2",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "The explicit-gap-via-scope-constraint pattern: when a chain definition's scope_constraints prohibit modification of a file (src/validate/*) that contains a stub with an inline comment attributing its wiring to the current task, the correct developer discipline is to (1) document the gap in open_questions output, (2) not silently omit mention of the undelivered wiring, and (3) name the follow-up task action explicitly ('should be queued as a follow-up developer task explicitly scoped to src/validate/index.ts'). This makes the gap visible in the audit trail at the point of ratification rather than surfacing as a surprise at integration time. The operator must now deliberately queue the follow-up task to close the wiring gap."
          }
        ]
      },
