        "bankings": [
          {
            "id": "B1",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "TypeScript Array.from phantom-cascade pattern: providing a single explicit type argument to Array.from<T>(iterable, mapfn) silently routes overload resolution to the 1-type-param overloads, which accept exactly 1 argument \u00e2\u20ac\u201d making the mapfn a superfluous second argument (TS2554). TypeScript error-recovery then infers the array element type as unknown, cascading to TS2571 and TS18046 errors throughout the function body that obscure the single root-cause site. In the GraphWrite Phase 1 task 1.6 instance, one root TS2554 produced four downstream cascade errors in src/iri/index.ts plus a second independent TS2554 in the test file \u00e2\u20ac\u201d six total errors from two occurrences of the same pattern. The diagnostic cue is a cluster of unknown-type errors following a single Array.from call."
          },
          {
            "id": "B2",
            "category": "methodology-refinement-candidate",
            "content": "Minimal-annotation fix discipline for TypeScript overload-resolution errors: when an explicit type argument causes incorrect overload selection, the correct repair is to remove the incorrect annotation and allow TypeScript to infer from the surrounding context (particularly the mapfn return type), rather than adding type assertions (as number), widening annotations, or switching to a different API. Removing the annotation is structurally lighter and forces the compiler to apply its own inference, which produces a more maintainable result \u00e2\u20ac\u201d the type contract is re-established through the function's logic rather than an authorial override. This discipline was confirmed in the task 119 developer output (self_assessment: confident; scope: minimal) and validated against the TypeScript 5.9.3 overload declarations during reconnaissance."
          }
        ]
