            "id": "B1",
            "category": "methodology-refinement-candidate",
            "content": "Task 1.12 (final Phase 1 task) operationalized the scope-split pattern at phase closure: the developer explicitly chose Option B (keep hand-rolled framework; add fast-check for the single deferred invariant only) over Option A (full Vitest/Jest migration rewriting all 14 test files), documented the deferred items with explicit gate conditions (OED-306, OED-313, CI-infrastructure phase), and named a follow-up chain for the three already-passing hand-rolled PBTs. This is the clearest Phase 1 instance of the discipline: distinguish 'blocking for closure' from 'additive quality improvement', deliver the former, forward-track the latter. The scope-split pattern as applied here is a Phase 1 methodology-refinement candidate worth formalizing as a named practice."
          },
          {
            "id": "B2",
            "category": "discipline-correction",
            "content": "When a scope-split selects an approach that conflicts with an authoritative IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN mandate (here: Option B keeps hand-rolled framework vs. \u00c2\u00a71.12's 'Configure Vitest/Jest'), the override must be captured in an ADR before the phase exit gate \u00e2\u20ac\u201d code-comment documentation is insufficient. DECISIONS.md currently contains ADR-001 through ADR-006 with no framework-choice record (recon F9). The IMPL_PLAN \u00c2\u00a71.12 mandate remains the sole formal authority and is now in silent conflict with the actual Phase 1 test codebase. The discipline: scope-split overrides of IMPL_PLAN sub-task mandates require a queued ADR ratification before the phase exit gate closes; otherwise the override is not auditable and creates a dormant conflict that will resurface at Phase 2 or Phase 4 exit gate review."
          },
          {
            "id": "B3",
            "category": "contingency-operationalization",
            "content": "The applier system agent adds UTF-8 BOM on new files per CLAUDE.md, but SPEC \u00c2\u00a75.3 rule 7 requires UTF-8 no-BOM for VMP canonical files. Changes C4, C5, C6 are all new files (before: null). If the applier adds a BOM, the golden-file byte-comparison test (active once OED-306+OED-313 close) will fail silently until that gate opens \u00e2\u20ac\u201d potentially months later. The operator must verify applier behavior for .jsonld files at commit-finalize; if BOM is added, a post-applier strip step is required. This contingency should be documented at the commit-finalize task level and at the Phase 1 exit gate checklist as a BOM-verification item for all new canonical fixture files."
          },
          {
            "id": "B4",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "C4 (test/fixtures/canonical-v0.4/minimal.jsonld) is committed as a pre-verified golden-file anchor: the file's key ordering is asserted to match serializeVmp output exactly, but no active test verifies this claim until OED-306+OED-313 close. This 'commit expected output, verify later' pattern creates a bit-rot window: if serializeVmp's key ordering changes between now and OED-313 closure, the committed fixture silently diverges. Mitigation pattern: add a canary unit test that loads C4, calls serializeVmp(JSON.parse(content)), and asserts output === content \u00e2\u20ac\u201d even before full golden-file machinery is active. This converts the pre-committed fixture from a passive claim into an actively-enforced invariant and closes the bit-rot window immediately."
          }
        ]
      },
