            "id": "B1",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "The first component extracted from App.tsx establishes the sibling-file convention for src/ui/: new components are placed as *.tsx siblings of App.tsx under src/ui/ rather than in a subdirectory (no src/ui/components/ exists and no IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN task specifies one). Tasks 2.3 (Term CRUD), 2.4 (React Flow Canvas), and 2.5 (Inspector) should follow this same sibling-file pattern unless a future architectural review explicitly decides to introduce a subdirectory. Establishing this convention at the first extraction avoids retrofit churn when three more major UI components land in Phase 2."
          },
          {
            "id": "B2",
            "category": "methodology-refinement-candidate",
            "content": "Canonical v0.4 fixture files authored manually (as in C6) depend on developer-traced SPEC \u00c2\u00a75.3 key-ordering rules without machine verification of serialize(parse(fixture))==fixture roundtrip idempotency. Developer open question 3 on task 166 flags this explicitly. A fixture-authoring checklist step \u00e2\u20ac\u201d run the canonical serializer over the new fixture and assert bytewise identity before committing \u00e2\u20ac\u201d would catch ordering drift silently introduced by hand-ordering. This is a low-ceremony pre-commit check that prevents silent fixture drift accumulating across Phase 2 task additions."
          }
        ]
