        "bankings": [
          {
            "id": "B1",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "The node:crypto / Web Crypto API split is a load-bearing seam that will recur in every UI task that exercises src/iri/ or any other Node-API-importing kernel module. src/iri/index.ts imports from 'node:crypto' (createHash, randomUUID), making it non-importable in a Vite browser bundle. The UI layer must use the Web Crypto API (crypto.randomUUID()) directly. The canonical resolution \u00e2\u20ac\u201d a browser-compatible re-export function in src/iri/ (e.g., `export function generateUuidUrn(): string { return 'urn:uuid:' + crypto.randomUUID(); }`) guarded by a tsconfig.ui.json-compatible build \u00e2\u20ac\u201d should be ratified and landed before Chain B, which will need a browser-compatible IRI generation path for the Edit IRI flow. Failing to resolve this before Chain B forces Chain B to also inline the bypass, compounding the divergence."
          },
          {
            "id": "B2",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "Unexported kernel helpers force UI-layer duplication: collectSemanticEntityIds in src/refactor/index.ts is not exported, forcing AddTermDialog.tsx to inline equivalent logic as collectExistingIris (Set<string> vs Map<string,string> \u00e2\u20ac\u201d different shape, equivalent for existence-checking). This is the first occurrence of a pattern where a kernel-layer helper that is load-bearing for UI correctness is not exported at the module boundary. The correct resolution is to export a public variant of the helper from src/refactor/ before Chain B, which will need IRI existence-checking for the Edit flow's duplicate-IRI warning. The discipline observation: kernel module public API surface should be designed with UI layer consumers in mind when the UI layer is a first-class consumer of the module."
          },
          {
            "id": "B3",
            "category": "methodology-refinement-candidate",
            "content": "The Chain A/B/C split for task 2.3 (Add flows in Chain A, Edit+Refactor-IRI in Chain B, imported read-only in Chain C) maps cleanly onto the SPEC FR groupings (FR-U006/007/008 vs FR-U009 vs FR-U010) and isolates the structurally simpler flows from those that require new kernel-layer integration (refactorIri for Chain B) and guard-logic design (FR-U010 structural enforcement for Chain C). This FR-grouping-as-chain-boundary pattern is a candidate methodology for planning future CRUD tasks: partition chains by the kernel dependencies each sub-flow introduces, not by UI similarity, so each chain can be ratified and verified against a minimal integration surface."
          }
        ]
      },
