          }
        ],
        "bankings": [
          {
            "id": "B1",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "Playwright fixture UUIDs follow a decade-gap allocation model (000020 \u00e2\u2020\u2019 000030 \u00e2\u2020\u2019 000040), where each fixture group reserves a decade-block and the next group opens at the next round ten. This is an implicit convention \u00e2\u20ac\u201d not documented in any spec or DECISIONS.md entry \u00e2\u20ac\u201d that creates natural spacing for future within-group additions without collision. The developer correctly extended the pattern to 000040 for the imported-term fixture group, but described it as 'next sequential', which is imprecise. A DECISIONS.md entry or fixture README naming this convention would make it explicit and prevent future developers from filling in 000033\u00e2\u20ac\u201c000039 as if they were available slots."
          },
          {
            "id": "B2",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "The reconnaissance agent surfaced four open questions, and the developer's proposal answered all four within the change rationale rather than leaving them as forward-tracked items. This 'recon-open-questions-as-developer-inputs' pattern produces tightly reconciled ratification surface: the architect can trace each recon question to a specific change or explicit deferral in the developer output, reducing ambiguity in the ruling. This pattern is worth noting as a discipline refinement candidate for future chain compositions where the recon and developer tasks are tightly coupled."
          }
        ]
      },
