        "bankings": [
          {
            "id": "B1",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "Chain-A read-only canvas derivation pattern: deriving React Flow edges directly from ecm:relations (source = ecm:subjectIri, target = ecm:objectIri) rather than joining through ecm:CanvasEdge entries in the active layout is a valid and deliberate simplification for the read-only chain scope. This approach renders all semantically-defined relations as canvas edges without filtering by per-layout edge presence, which is correct when the user cannot yet manipulate which relations appear on a given layout. The join through ecm:CanvasEdge \u00e2\u20ac\u201d needed to honour per-layout edge visibility and to consume ecm:sourceHandle/ecm:targetHandle for custom connection routing \u00e2\u20ac\u201d belongs to the layout write-back chain (Chain C). The pattern establishes a scope ladder: read-only derivation chains consume the simplest projection of the canonical document; write-back chains add the join to maintain per-layout fidelity."
          },
          {
            "id": "B2",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "CSS-class-based Playwright assertions against third-party UI library internal class names are an acceptable acceptance-criterion pattern when three conditions are jointly met: (1) the library uses stable, documented class naming conventions across major versions (@xyflow/react has used .react-flow__node and .react-flow__edge consistently through v10\u00e2\u20ac\u201cv12); (2) assertions are scoped to a container element with a stable data-testid, isolating library-internal DOM from the surrounding app shell; (3) the assertion uses retry-and-timeout semantics (Playwright toHaveCount with an explicit timeout) rather than point-in-time snapshots, accommodating async rendering cycles including ResizeObserver initialisation and fitView layout passes. When these three conditions hold, the test accurately validates the rendering contract without requiring the implementer to inject custom data-testid attributes into library-managed DOM, which would require a custom node component and additional test surface. When any condition fails \u00e2\u20ac\u201d e.g., the library renames its internal classes in a semver-major bump \u00e2\u20ac\u201d the test fails at the CSS selector, surfacing the breakage immediately."
          },
          {
            "id": "B3",
            "category": "methodology-refinement-candidate",
            "content": "The developer's self_assessment: 'uncertain' field is a useful ratification-chain signal that surfaces advisory build-time risks without blocking ratification. As a methodology refinement candidate: ratification of new UI component changes that introduce third-party library dependencies should carry an explicit post-apply verification obligation in the operator chain composition \u00e2\u20ac\u201d specifically, applier \u00e2\u2020\u2019 test-runner (npm run build) \u00e2\u2020\u2019 test-runner (npm test). The test-runner system agent (v2.9.0) provides the substrate; what is currently missing is an operator-discipline convention that makes the post-apply build/test step mandatory for this artifact class rather than advisory. This is analogous to the artifact-kind chain composition table in CLAUDE.md \u00c2\u00a77.8, which already distinguishes canonical-doc from code artifact chains; a further row for 'new UI component with new third-party devDep' that mandates build+test-runner in the chain would absorb this class of advisory uncertainty at composition time rather than ratification time."
          }
        ]
      },
