        "bankings": [
          {
            "id": "B1",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "The ReactFlowProvider outer-wrapper / useReactFlow inner-consumer split is now the canonical CanvasView component shape for any chain that requires access to React Flow internal APIs (screenToFlowPosition for Chain B, useViewport for Chain C, etc.). The outer CanvasView export retains its public prop interface and null-guard; the inner CanvasViewInner component is the React Flow API consumer. Future chains extending canvas interactivity should follow this split rather than attempting to call useReactFlow at the CanvasView level."
          },
          {
            "id": "B2",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "The inline find-or-create pattern for ecm:CanvasLayout (find first layout by type guard; create one with generated IRI + Default Layout name if absent) is the first instance of canvas-state initialization logic in the UI layer. This pattern will recur in Chain C (move node / layout persistence) and any future chain that writes to ecm:layouts. If this logic grows in complexity \u00e2\u20ac\u201d e.g., to enforce SPEC \u00c2\u00a75.11 mandatory fields on the created layout or to handle multi-layout scenarios \u00e2\u20ac\u201d extracting a shared canvas utility function (e.g., src/ui/canvasUtils.ts) would reduce duplication and provide a single point for SPEC compliance enforcement."
          },
          {
            "id": "B3",
            "category": "methodology-refinement-candidate",
            "content": "The developer's open_questions output in task 191 explicitly surfaces three Chain C/D concerns: fitView flip-on-first-create, onPaneClick event-detail semantics as an implementation assumption, and SPEC \u00c2\u00a75.11 compliance gaps in newly-created layouts. This chain-boundary handoff via open_questions is the established forwarding mechanism for deferred concerns in GraphWrite chain-scoped development. The pattern is proving robust: it prevents scope creep in the current chain while creating legible, file-and-line-grounded inputs for the next chain's reconnaissance. Worth codifying as a named practice in operator methodology documentation."
          }
        ]
