        "bankings": [
          {
            "id": "B1",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "Recon-guided incidental interface closure: the reconnaissance agent surfaced a gap between the EcmCanvasNode TypeScript interface (3 fields) and the write path / fixture (5 fields). The developer addressed this as change C1 within the same chain rather than deferring it to a separate task. This is a healthy pattern \u00e2\u20ac\u201d recon findings that are non-blocking for the primary change but represent maintenance hazards are most efficiently closed in the same chain by the developer who already has the file in scope. The cost is near-zero (the C1 change is 3 lines); the benefit is that the interface no longer silently misrepresents the schema's actual field set."
          },
          {
            "id": "B2",
            "category": "methodology-refinement-candidate",
            "content": "Viewport-scale-invariant position assertions for Playwright drag tests: when fitView is active on a React Flow canvas, the screen-to-flow coordinate mapping depends on the container size and viewport zoom factor at render time, making precise flow-coordinate assertions fragile across CI environments. C3 uses a relative assertion (at least one node's position differs from every known original position by >1 unit) rather than asserting an absolute coordinate. This pattern is reusable for any Playwright test that involves drag on a fitView canvas \u00e2\u20ac\u201d assert 'position changed' rather than 'position equals expected', and reserve precise coordinate assertions for cases where the viewport zoom is under test control."
          }
        ]
      },
