        "bankings": [
          {
            "id": "B1",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "The AC4 collectAllKeys recursive tree-walk pattern (recursing into both array items and nested object values before asserting an absent-key property) is the correct canonical shape for 'no internal-state leakage' assertions on deeply nested JSON documents. A naive Object.keys check at only the top-level document object would pass even when prohibited keys are nested inside subdocument arrays (e.g., ecm:layouts[*].ecm:nodes[*]). Whenever a test needs to assert the total absence of a key-name pattern in a JSON tree, the recursive descent \u00e2\u20ac\u201d not the top-level scan \u00e2\u20ac\u201d is the load-bearing approach. This pattern should be cited in future Playwright test authoring for any 'no X present anywhere in the saved document' criterion."
          },
          {
            "id": "B2",
            "category": "methodology-refinement-candidate",
            "content": "When a planned emitter format is deferred (here: semantic JSON-LD emitter, forward-tracked as ft-112), an existing emitter that shares the identical internal projection pipeline (here: Turtle, which calls projectSemantic internally as step 1) is a sound functional stand-in for integration-level acceptance tests of the projection's exclusion behavior. The stand-in is valid precisely because the behavioral property under test (canvas-type exclusion) is a property of the shared projection step, not of the downstream serialization format. This 'projection-pipeline stand-in' discipline provides a principled basis for keeping integration tests green during emitter deferral without compromising the acceptance criteria chain."
          }
        ]
