        "ruling": "ratified",
        "editorial_verdict": "substantive",
        "editorial_verdict_reason": "The change introduces new behavioral handlers (handleConnect, handleEdgeClick), a new component file (Inspector.tsx), conditional prop changes to ReactFlow (nodesConnectable, elementsSelectable), new state in App.tsx, and a new Playwright test file\u00e2\u20ac\u201dall of which alter observable runtime behavior rather than adjusting text.",
        "rationale": "Reconnaissance (task 210) is present in UPSTREAM. Chain A scope is appropriately bounded: FR-U014 draw-to-create is implemented via handleConnect; edge selection is wired end-to-end (handleEdgeClick \u00e2\u2020\u2019 onEdgeSelect \u00e2\u2020\u2019 App.selectedRelationId \u00e2\u2020\u2019 Inspector); Inspector.tsx is a read-only skeleton that doesn't over-build toward tasks 2.7\u00e2\u20ac\u201c2.10; AC1 is covered; AC2\u00e2\u20ac\u201cAC4 are explicitly deferred to Chain B with a detailed specification.\n\nRecon findings reconciled: F2 (nodesConnectable={false}) resolved by C5 \u00e2\u20ac\u201d enabled conditionally mirroring nodesDraggable; F3 (elementsSelectable={false}) resolved by C5 same pattern; F4 (no onConnect/onEdgeClick) resolved by C5; F14 (onProjectChange pathway) and F15 (mutation pattern) followed correctly in handleConnect; F16 (.gw-inspector CSS already present) confirmed \u00e2\u20ac\u201d no CSS addition needed; F19 (no Inspector.tsx) resolved by C8. The recon open-question OQ-2 (single chain vs. two chains) is answered by the developer's Chain A/B split, which the recon summary independently recommended.\n\nApplier before-snippet fidelity verified: C1, C2, C3, C4, C5, C6, C7 before-snippets match actual CanvasView.tsx content as read; C9, C10, C11, C12 before-snippets match actual App.tsx content as read.\n\nLayer boundaries respected: all changes are in src/ui/; no imports from src/kernel/, src/validate/, or src/emit/ introduced by the UI components.\n\nEvent 8 lesson applied: C13 AC1 uses mouse.move/mouse.down/mouse.move(steps:15)/mouse.up for the drag gesture rather than dblclick, correctly scoped to handle-position discovery and bounding-box targeting. The developer's open_question about `.react-flow__handle.source` vs `[data-handletype=\"source\"]` selector is appropriately flagged and requires one test-server run before CI gating.\n\nTwo items require operator decision before Chain B is queued:\n\n(1) ecm:UnassignedPredicate sentinel \u00e2\u20ac\u201d Recon OQ-1 explicitly asked the architect to rule on the predicate approach before development. The developer proceeded with the sentinel without this ruling. For Chain A/AC1 scope the sentinel is acceptable: the AC1 test does not verify ecm:predicateIri, and the MALFORMED_RELATION hard error (SPEC \u00c2\u00a717.2) requires predicateIri to be absent/null, which the sentinel avoids. However, the sentinel WILL trigger DANGLING_RELATION_PREDICATE_REF because 'ecm:UnassignedPredicate' is not a term in ecm:terms. Before Chain B is queued, the operator must decide: (a) Chain B includes retroactive cleanup of any persisted ecm:UnassignedPredicate relations before the user saves, OR (b) the sentinel in persisted state is accepted, with validation errors surfaced in task 2.8's display. The architect rules both are architecturally valid. The modal-gate approach (OQ-1 option a: block edge creation until predicate is chosen) is the cleanest from a data-integrity standpoint but adds interaction complexity for Chain A; the sentinel approach is the correct pragmatic MVP choice, provided Chain B has a documented cleanup path.\n\n(2) IRI generation helper \u00e2\u20ac\u201d handleConnect uses `crypto.randomUUID()` inline (`urn:uuid:${crypto.randomUUID()}`) rather than generateIri() from src/iri/index.ts. This follows the exact precedent established by handlePaneClick (CanvasView.tsx line 221) and is not a blocking concern. However, the review focus specifically flagged this. The UI layer is outside the purity constraint; generateIri() with ecm:uuid-urn policy calls generateUuidV4() internally, which is functionally equivalent but centralizes the pattern. A future chain or task-2.5+ refactor should unify UI-layer IRI generation through a shared helper to prevent the inline pattern from accumulating as a pattern debt.\n\nInspector.tsx correctly accepts onProjectChange in its props but does not use it in Chain A, making the prop shape stable for Chain B expansion without requiring App.tsx changes at that time. The duplicate isEcmRelation type guard (CanvasView.tsx vs Inspector.tsx) is intentional and bounded \u00e2\u20ac\u201d the developer flagged shared extraction as a future refactor, which is the correct minimal-viable posture.",
        "referenced_evidence": [
          {
            "type": "upstream_task",
            "id": "urn:fnsr:task:210-recon-relation-crud",
            "field": "outputs.findings[F2,F3,F4,F7,F9,F13,F14,F15,F16,F19]"
          },
          {
            "type": "upstream_task",
            "id": "urn:fnsr:task:210-recon-relation-crud",
            "field": "outputs.open_questions[OQ-1,OQ-2]"
          },
