            "source": "project/DECISIONS.md"
          }
        ],
        "bankings": [
          {
            "id": "B1",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "Dangling-reference-on-delete pattern: Inspector's handleDelete clears the relation from project['ecm:relations'] via onProjectChange but does not reset selectedRelationId to null in App.tsx. The correct empty-state display is achieved via the rel===undefined guard in the Inspector render path. This pattern is sound when the selection ID has a single consumer with a complete guard, but becomes a state-hygiene liability if additional consumers check selectedRelationId !== null for affordances (context menus, keyboard shortcuts, status bars) without also verifying the referenced relation exists. The load-bearing condition is 'Inspector is the only consumer of selectedRelationId'; if that changes, the pattern requires a dedicated onRelationDelete callback or an App.tsx-level derived null-coercion."
          },
          {
            "id": "B2",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "Chain-isolation duplication pattern operationalized across a second boundary: C1 deliberately duplicates iriTail (from TermSidebar.tsx) and the partitionTerms filter logic as getObjectPropertyOptions (also from TermSidebar.tsx) into Inspector.tsx as local-only helpers, continuing the codebase pattern established for the EcmRelation interface (recon F14). The pattern's rationale is component-level autonomy across implementation chains. The natural extraction inflection point is when three or more components declare structurally equivalent helpers; at that threshold a shared src/ui/utils.ts or src/ui/types.ts becomes load-bearing rather than merely convenient."
          }
        ]
      },
