        "bankings": [
          {
            "id": "B1",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "The 'mutual-exclusion-at-parent-state' pattern for multi-mode inspector panels: App.tsx holds both selectedRelationId and selectedInstanceId as independent state variables and enforces mutual exclusion in the edge/node select callbacks (clearing the other on each selection event). The Inspector component receives both and renders based on which is non-null, with no arbitration logic of its own. This keeps the Inspector a pure render function of its props and locates the single source of truth for selection mode at the App level \u00e2\u20ac\u201d a pattern worth encoding as a guideline for future multi-mode panel components."
          },
          {
            "id": "B2",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "The elementsSelectable prop coupling in CanvasView bundles node-selectability with node-draggability and node-connectability under a single onProjectChange !== undefined gate. This creates an implicit 'read-only mode' that disables selection, drag, and connect simultaneously. In the current usage (App always passes onProjectChange), this is not a problem. However, if a future host wants a 'view-only with selection' mode (e.g., for literal inspection without drag permission), the current gate would need to be split into independent props. This architectural constraint is worth tracking as the canvas feature set grows."
          },
          {
            "id": "B3",
            "category": "methodology-refinement-candidate",
            "content": "The ecm:createdAt/ecm:updatedAt absence from newly-created ecm:LiteralAssertion objects (AddLiteralDialog does not populate them) creates a divergence between the SPEC \u00c2\u00a75.10 example schema and the actual runtime shape of assertions created by the UI. The IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN ACs do not require timestamp fields, the recon's F2 enumeration omitted them, and the type guard does not check them \u00e2\u20ac\u201d so the divergence is within task scope. However, this pattern (SPEC example includes audit timestamps; UI implementation omits them) may accumulate across future CRUD tasks if not resolved. A phase-exit doc-pass should determine whether ecm:createdAt/ecm:updatedAt are normatively required on all sub-document types or merely illustrative in SPEC examples."
          }
        ]
      },
