        "bankings": [
          {
            "id": "B1",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "The deriveIsAboutState pattern \u00e2\u20ac\u201d reading document fields directly to derive a reactive UI indicator state, mirroring validator discrimination logic without calling validate() \u00e2\u20ac\u201d is an architectural trade-off first instantiated at task 2.9. It avoids validation overhead on every React render cycle but introduces a dual-path drift risk: if src/validate/index.ts updates its discrimination logic (e.g., adds a third document marker), deriveIsAboutState must be updated in lockstep. The discipline for managing this class of mirrored-logic pairs is: (1) document the mirroring relationship explicitly in both files, (2) add a unit test that compares deriveIsAboutState outputs against validate() outputs for all three canonical document states. Future UI features that derive state from document content without running full validation should follow this same pattern."
          },
          {
            "id": "B2",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "The undefined-assignment-as-field-clear pattern (`updated[\"ecm:_legacyAnchorPlaceholder\"] = undefined`) relies on JSON.stringify silently omitting keys with undefined values \u00e2\u20ac\u201d standard JavaScript behavior, but implicit and likely to surprise future developers unfamiliar with this contract. The pattern is structurally safe in GraphWrite because serializeVmp uses JSON.stringify with a null replacer (verified at canonicalize.ts:266). The discipline is: when using this pattern, annotate the intent with a comment explaining why undefined is used rather than delete, and confirm that any intermediate serializers in the path also use no custom replacer that would convert undefined to null."
          }
        ]
