        "bankings": [
          {
            "id": "B1",
            "category": "methodology-refinement-candidate",
            "content": "Reconnaissance findings can become stale when a parallel chain (Chain A) lands UI work between the reconnaissance dispatch and the developer dispatch. In this cycle, recon findings F1 and F5 reported class-assignment UI as absent; by developer dispatch, Chain A had landed the UI at Inspector.tsx lines 315\u00e2\u20ac\u201c386, making F1/F5 inaccurate. The developer correctly identified the discrepancy via direct file reading and disclosed it in open_questions. The architect resolved the conflict by independently re-reading the file. A methodology refinement candidate: for multi-chain Phase deliverables where chains share UI surface, the operator should consider sequencing reconnaissance AFTER all prerequisite chains are committed, or explicitly flagging reconnaissance outputs as 'snapshot-at-time-T' with the commit SHA to make staleness detectable without re-reading."
          },
          {
            "id": "B2",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "The developer's open_questions field in the developer-agent output functioned as a risk-disclosure surface for three distinct flakiness categories (selector resolution, render-race, DOM ordering) that are below the blocking threshold but above the ignore threshold. This pattern \u00e2\u20ac\u201d using open_questions as an advisory risk register rather than a blocking question queue \u00e2\u20ac\u201d is effective for smoke-test-level work where some inherent test instability is acceptable and the operator can decide at runtime whether to apply the suggested guards. Worth preserving as a named pattern for future developer task contracts at the smoke/integration test level."
